<p class=3D"mw-empty-elt">


</p>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Sphere_wireframe_10deg_6r.svg=
" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wi=
kipedia/commons/thumb/7/7e/Sphere_wireframe_10deg_6r.svg/250px-Sphere_wiref=
rame_10deg_6r.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"250" clas=
s=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"800" data-file-height=3D"800"></a>=
<figcaption>A <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sph=
ere">sphere</a> of radius <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:=
italic;">r</span> has surface area <span class=3D"texhtml">4<i>=CF=80r</i><=
sup>2</sup></span>.</figcaption></figure>
<p>The <b>surface area</b> (symbol <i><b>A</b></i>) of a <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Solid_geometry" title=3D"Solid geometry">solid</a> o=
bject is a measure of the total <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ar=
ea" title=3D"Area">area</a> that the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Surface_(mathematics)" title=3D"Surface (mathematics)">surface</a> of th=
e object occupies.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The mathema=
tical definition of surface area in the presence of curved surfaces is cons=
iderably more involved than the definition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Arc_length" title=3D"Arc length">arc length</a> of one-dimensio=
nal curves, or of the surface area for <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Polyhedra" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Polyhedra">polyhedra</a> (i.=
e., objects with flat polygonal <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fa=
ce_(geometry)" title=3D"Face (geometry)">faces</a>), for which the surface =
area is the sum of the areas of its faces. Smooth surfaces, such as a <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a>, ar=
e assigned surface area using their representation as <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parametric_surface" title=3D"Parametric surface">parame=
tric surfaces</a>. This definition of surface area is based on methods of <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal_calculus" class=3D"mw=
-redirect" title=3D"Infinitesimal calculus">infinitesimal calculus</a> and =
involves <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Partial_derivative" title=
=3D"Partial derivative">partial derivatives</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Double_integration" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Double=
 integration">double integration</a>.
</p><p>A general definition of surface area was sought by <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Lebesgue" title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Henri Lebe=
sgue</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Minkowski" ti=
tle=3D"Hermann Minkowski">Hermann Minkowski</a> at the turn of the twentiet=
h century. Their work led to the development of <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Geometric_measure_theory" title=3D"Geometric measure theory">=
geometric measure theory</a>, which studies various notions of surface area=
 for irregular objects of any dimension. An important example is the <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Minkowski_content" title=3D"Minkowski co=
ntent">Minkowski content</a> of a surface.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Definition">Definition</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSurface_area&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D1" title=3D"Edit section: Definition"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>While the areas of many simple surfaces have been known since antiquity,=
 a rigorous mathematical <i>definition</i> of area requires a great deal of=
 care.
This should provide a function
