<p>Surface areas of flat polygonal shapes must agree with their geometrical=
ly defined <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area" title=3D"Area">ar=
ea</a>. Since surface area is a geometric notion, areas of <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Congruence_(geometry)" title=3D"Congruence (geomet=
ry)">congruent</a> surfaces must be the same and the area must depend only =
on the shape of the surface, but not on its position and orientation in spa=
ce. This means that surface area is invariant under the <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_group" title=3D"Euclidean group">group of E=
uclidean motions</a>. These properties uniquely characterize surface area f=
or a wide class of geometric surfaces called <i>piecewise smooth</i>. Such =
surfaces consist of finitely many pieces that can be represented in the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parametric_surface" title=3D"Parametr=
ic surface">parametric form</a>
