-align: -0.338ex; width:2.064ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle N}"=
></span> tend to infinity doesn't converge. In particular it doesn't conver=
ge to the area of the cylinder.</figcaption></figure><p>One of the subtleti=
es of surface area, as compared to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Arc_length" title=3D"Arc length">arc length</a> of curves, is that surface=
 area cannot be defined simply as the limit of areas of polyhedral shapes a=
pproximating a given smooth surface. It was demonstrated by <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Schwarz" title=3D"Hermann Schwarz">Herman=
n Schwarz</a> that already for the cylinder, different choices of approxima=
ting flat surfaces can lead to different limiting values of the area; this =
example is known as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schwarz_la=
ntern" title=3D"Schwarz lantern">Schwarz lantern</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-sc=
h1_2-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surfac=
e_area#cite_note-sch1-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-sch2_3-0" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#cite_note-=
sch2-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>Various approaches to a general definition of surface area were deve=
loped in the late nineteenth and the early twentieth century by <a href=3D"=
https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Lebesgue" title=3D"Henri Lebesgue">Henr=
i Lebesgue</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Minkows=
ki" title=3D"Hermann Minkowski">Hermann Minkowski</a>. While for piecewise =
smooth surfaces there is a unique natural notion of surface area, if a surf=
ace is very irregular, or rough, then it may not be possible to assign an a=
rea to it at all. A typical example is given by a surface with spikes sprea=
d throughout in a dense fashion. Many surfaces of this type occur in the st=
udy of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fractal" title=3D"Fractal">=
fractals</a>. Extensions of the notion of area which partially fulfill its =
function and may be defined even for very badly irregular surfaces are stud=
ied in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_measure_theory" t=
itle=3D"Geometric measure theory">geometric measure theory</a>. A specific =
example of such an extension is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Minkowski_content" title=3D"Minkowski content">Minkowski content</a> of t=
he surface.
</p>
