<p>The below given formulas can be used to show that the surface area of a =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">sphere</a=
> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder_(geometry)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cylinder (geometry)">cylinder</a> of the same rad=
ius and height are in the ratio <b>2&nbsp;:&nbsp;3</b>, as follows.
</p><p>Let the radius be <i>r</i> and the height be <i>h</i> (which is 2<i>=
r</i> for the sphere).
</p><p><span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-block"><span class=
=3D"mwe-math-mathml-display mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;">=
<math display=3D"block" xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" alttex=
t=3D"{\displaystyle {\begin{array}{rlll}{\text{Sphere surface area}}&amp;=
=3D4\pi r^{2}&amp;&amp;=3D(2\pi r^{2})\times 2\\{\text{Cylinder surface are=
a}}&amp;=3D2\pi r(h+r)&amp;=3D2\pi r(2r+r)&amp;=3D(2\pi r^{2})\times 3\end{=
array}}}">
  <semantics>
