r(2r+r)&amp;=3D(2\pi r^{2})\times 3\end{array}}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/30f653fcee1bca71787f36bebe33d36811bf3d84" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-display mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertica=
l-align: -2.671ex; width:68.74ex; height:6.509ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle {\=
begin{array}{rlll}{\text{Sphere surface area}}&amp;=3D4\pi r^{2}&amp;&amp;=
=3D(2\pi r^{2})\times 2\\{\text{Cylinder surface area}}&amp;=3D2\pi r(h+r)&=
amp;=3D2\pi r(2r+r)&amp;=3D(2\pi r^{2})\times 3\end{array}}}"></span>
</p><p>The discovery of this ratio is credited to <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a>.<sup id=3D"=
cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Su=
rface_area#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_chemistry">In chemistry<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSurface_area=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Edit section: In chemistry"><s=
pan>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></=
div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Surface_area.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descriptio=
n"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/51/Su=
rface_area.svg/250px-Surface_area.svg.png" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250"=
 height=3D"141" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"1280" data-fil=
e-height=3D"720"></a><figcaption>Surface area of particles of different siz=
es.</figcaption></figure>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
See also: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Accessible_surface_area"=
 title=3D"Accessible surface area">Accessible surface area</a></div>
<p>Surface area is important in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ch=
emical_kinetics" title=3D"Chemical kinetics">chemical kinetics</a>. Increas=
ing the surface area of a substance generally increases the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reaction_rate" title=3D"Reaction rate">rate</a> o=
f a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chemical_reaction" title=3D"Ch=
emical reaction">chemical reaction</a>. For example, <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Iron" title=3D"Iron">iron</a> in a fine powder will <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Combustion" title=3D"Combustion">combu=
st</a>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-5" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#cite_note-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> while in solid blocks =
it is stable enough to use in structures. For different applications a mini=
mal or maximal surface area may be desired.
</p>
<div style=3D"clear:both;" class=3D""></div>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"In_biology">In biology</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DSurface_area&amp=
;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: In biology"><span>ed=
it</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Mitochondrion_186.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/6/68/Mitochondrion_186.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"186" heigh=
t=3D"189" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"186" data-file-heigh=
t=3D"189"></a><figcaption>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Inne=
r_membrane_of_the_mitochondrion" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Inner membr=
ane of the mitochondrion">inner membrane of the mitochondrion</a> has a lar=
ge surface area due to infoldings, allowing higher rates of <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cellular_respiration" title=3D"Cellular respirati=
on">cellular respiration</a> (electron <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Micrograph" title=3D"Micrograph">micrograph</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area=
#cite_note-6"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup></figcaption></figure>
<p>The surface area of an organism is important in several considerations, =
such as regulation of body temperature and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Digestion" title=3D"Digestion">digestion</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7=
" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area=
#cite_note-7"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> Animals use their <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Teeth" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Teeth">teeth</a> to grind fo=
od down into smaller particles, increasing the surface area available for d=
igestion.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-8" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#cite_note-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>8<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The epithelial tissu=
e lining the digestive tract contains <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Microvilli" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Microvilli">microvilli</a>, =
greatly increasing the area available for absorption.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-9"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#=
cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-brac=
ket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elephant" =
title=3D"Elephant">Elephants</a> have large <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Ear" title=3D"Ear">ears</a>, allowing them to regulate their own =
body temperature.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area#cite_note-10"><span class=3D"cite-b=
racket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In other =
instances, animals will need to minimize surface area;<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1=
1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_are=
a#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> for example, people will fold their arms over t=
heir chest when cold to minimize heat loss.
</p><p>The <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Surface_area_to_volume_=
ratio" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Surface area to volume ratio">surface=
 area to volume ratio</a> (SA:V) of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Cell_(biology)" title=3D"Cell (biology)">cell</a> imposes upper limits =
on size, as the volume increases much faster than does the surface area, th=
us limiting the rate at which substances diffuse from the interior across t=
he <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cell_membrane" title=3D"Cell me=
mbrane">cell membrane</a> to interstitial spaces or to other cells.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Surface_area#cite_note-12"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Indeed, representing a cell as an=
 idealized <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere=
">sphere</a> of radius <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:ita=
lic;">r</span>, the volume and surface area are, respectively, <span class=
=3D"texhtml"><i>V</i> =3D (4/3)<i>=CF=80r</i><sup>3</sup></span> and <span =
class=3D"texhtml"><i>SA</i> =3D 4<i>=CF=80r</i><sup>2</sup></span>. The res=
ulting surface area to volume ratio is therefore <span class=3D"texhtml">3/=
<i>r</i></span>. Thus, if a cell has a radius of 1 =CE=BCm, the SA:V ratio =
is 3; whereas if the radius of the cell is instead 10 =CE=BCm, then the SA:=
V ratio becomes 0.3. With a cell radius of 100, SA:V ratio is 0.03. Thus, t=
he surface area falls off steeply with increasing volume.
</p>
